        ii.
            (21.65 + 21.3 + 21.5)/3 = 21.48333 ~= 21.48 cm^3
    c.
        The student should perform the titration once again; i.e.
            1. Add sodium hydroxide solution into the beaker using a pipette of 25 cm^3 capacity, taking care to take the reading at eye-level at the bottom of the meniscus;
            2. Add dilute nitric acid of the same concentration into the burette;
            3. Add exactly 21.48 cm^3 of dilute nitric acid into the beaker using the burette;
            4. Allow the resultant solution to evaporate and crystalise on a watch-glass or similar until there is no/little liquid left
            5. During this process, crystals will form.
            6. Pat dry using a paper towel, and then leave on some paper towel and allow it to further air-dry if necessary
        Noting that no indicator is added in the titration as it is not necessary and would result in impure crystals of sodium nitrate.
6.
    a.
        The crude oil is separated into fractions by fractional distilation by:
            1. Heating the crude oil until it vaporizes
            2. Passing the vapor into a fractionating column
            3. The fractionating column has a gradient of temperature; i.e. it is cooler at the top and warmer at the bottom
            4. Different fractions of crude oil condense at different places in the fractionating column (at their boiling points)
            5. These can be extracted from those points.
    b.
